{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604589"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:56:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:56:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15847"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15847"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.86,0,0.07,0,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8538"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71556"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8538"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2024-11-19T00:09:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-18T14:48:25+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2024-11-19T00:13:53+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-29 15:00:49"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15847"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"17831"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57050"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7033"},{"type":"tags","id":"10609"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20484"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20487"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57050"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71556","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71556"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for preconception counselling. She and her partner have been trying to conceive for three months. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has regular menstrual cycles every 28 days. On examination, she appears well with vital signs are within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of the fallopian tubes in fertilisation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Provision of an environment for sperm capacitation and fertilisation","Production of progesterone to support early pregnancy","Storage of mature oocytes until fertilisation","Secretion of hormones to trigger ovulation","Formation of the corpus luteum after ovulation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe fallopian tubes, also known as oviducts or uterine tubes, play a crucial role in human reproduction. \u003Cstrong\u003EProvision of an environment for sperm capacitation and fertilisation\u003C/strong\u003E is their primary function. The tubes create an optimal microenvironment through ciliary movement and secretory functions that support both sperm capacitation (the physiological changes sperm must undergo to become capable of fertilising an egg) and the fertilisation process itself.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of mature oocytes\u003C/strong\u003E is not a function of the fallopian tubes. After ovulation, the oocyte remains viable for only about 24 hours and must be fertilised within this window. The tubes transport the oocyte but do not store it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of progesterone\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the function of the corpus luteum in the ovary. Progesterone is essential for maintaining early pregnancy and preparing the endometrium for implantation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of hormones to trigger ovulation\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily the function of the anterior pituitary gland, which releases luteinising hormone (LH) to trigger ovulation. The fallopian tubes do not have an endocrine function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of the corpus luteum\u003C/strong\u003E occurs in the ovary after ovulation, when the remnants of the ovarian follicle transform into the corpus luteum. This does not involve the fallopian tubes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe fallopian tubes are specifically adapted for their reproductive role with specialised epithelium containing both ciliated and secretory cells. The cilia help transport the oocyte and early embryo, while the secretory cells produce nutrients and factors that support fertilisation and early embryonic development. Fertilisation typically occurs in the ampulla of the fallopian tube, and the resulting embryo is transported to the uterus over 3-4 days.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The fallopian tubes provide the optimal environment for fertilisation. Its secretory functions contribute to capacitation of sperm and ciliary function perform egg pickup, egg transport and subsequently transport of the embryo to the uterus.","Fertilisation typically occurs in the ampulla of the fallopian tube within 24 hours of ovulation."],"references":["Ikawa M, Inoue N, Benham AM, Okabe M. Fertilization: a sperm\u0027s journey to and interaction with the oocyte. J Clin Invest. 2010 Apr;120(4):984-94. doi: 10.1172/JCI41585. Epub 2010 Apr 1. PMID: 20364096; PMCID: PMC2846064","Coy P, Garc\u00eda-V\u00e1zquez FA, Visconti PE, Avil\u00e9s M. Roles of the oviduct in mammalian fertilization. Reproduction. 2012 Dec;144(6):649-60. doi: 10.1530/REP-12-0279. Epub 2012 Oct 1. PMID: 23028122; PMCID: PMC4022750","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57050"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15847"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57050","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57050"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T13:20:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T08:40:21+10:30","number":5,"notes":"- Minor changes in explanation\n- First and third learning point essentially explaining the same, combined and added information to first learning point","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-04T08:39:22+10:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-8538-5.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250930%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250930T032602Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=b0da6a496a79552e1c0e4d8d053e7d51ef927e834807d002065afb46e296dc1a"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8538"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71556"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"22113"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","p